                        <h4>Tour: Spellbinding Highland Tales</h4>
                        <p> <b>Activity Level</b> : 3</p><hr>
                        <p>Scotland's enchanting splendour will simply take your breath away!</p>
                        <p>Delight the senses on a journey to the top-20 rated Cairngorns National Park, with an unforgettable guided highland adventure through stunning scenery.

Marvel where clans clashed in defence of the realm, as you explore spectacular Balmoral Castle to hear tales of noble life, and to Dunrobin, a true jewel in the Scottish Highlands Crown, strikingly built in the enchanting style of a French Chateau.

Observe wonderful wildlife on a new kind of birdwatching experience, before an encounter with masterfully directed sheepdogs at work, commanding their herd in lush green countryside.</p><hr><h4>Hotels: Grant Arms Hotel</h4><p><p>A warm Highland welcome awaits you at the magnificent Grant Arms Hotel, home of the Bird Watching and Wildlife Club Awarded a gold star for scoring in the top ten percent of its star rating, its former famous visitors include both Queen Victoria and Queen Elizabeth II. In the fine Scottish country town of Grantown on Spey, not far from the famous Spey River, lies the handsome stone built Grant Arms Hotel, which has recently been refurbished and upgraded to offer modern comforts whilst retaining a traditional character. Strathspey and the Cairngorms National Park is renowned for its magnificent scenery and diversity of wildlife. Wherever you go the commanding Cairngorm Mountain Range is always there in the background. The Hotel is perfectly based not only for bird and wildlife watching, but also for walking around right in the centre of the town! Our Restaurant is a delightful setting to enjoy the delicious meals cooked by Head Chef Chris Grant and his team, who use the very best of local produce to create their dishes, after your evening meal you can enjoy our extensive array of Speyside Malt Whiskies in the Capercaillie Bar. All facilities in the Grant Arms Hotel are wheelchair accessible.</p></p><p>A warm Highland welcome awaits you at the recently refurbished, handsome and magnificent Grant Arms Hotel, home of the Bird Watching and Wildlife Club Awarded a gold star for scoring in the top ten percent of its star rating, and where former visitors include both Queen Victoria and Queen Elizabeth II. Located in the fine Scottish country town of Grantown on Spey, not far from the famous Spey River,  where only the very best local produce is used by  Head Chef Chris Grant and his team, why not taste a Speyside Malt Whisky in the Capercaillie Bar as you enjoy the stunning backdrop of the Cairngorm Mountain Range?</p><h4>Hotels: Peebles Hydro</h4><p><p>A beautiful early 20th Century hotel, surrounded by forest, Peebles Hydro offers us a comfortable traditional oasis for our stay. Features include genuine Scottish breakfasts, indoor pool and gym, high-speed Wi-Fi, spectacular views and Peeble&rsquo;s very own gin distillery.</p></p><p>A beautiful early 20th Century hotel, surrounded by forest, Peebles Hydro offers us a comfortable traditional oasis for our stay. Features include genuine Scottish breakfasts, indoor pool and gym, high-speed Wi-Fi, spectacular views and Peeble&rsquo;s very own gin distillery.</p><h4>Hotels: Oxford Witney Hotel</h4><p></p><p>Built in the old Cotswold style, Oxford Witney is in the heart of Oxfordshire. Oxford is just 10 miles away and Burford is within 7 miles of the building.

Near Burford and the Cotswolds, Oxford Witney Hotel features a free-to-use swimming pool and an air-conditioned gym. Witney town centre is a 20-minute walk from the building.

The 93 en-suite bedrooms at the 4-star Oxford Witney each have a digital TV, safe and tea & coffee making facilities. </p><h4>Experience: Dunrobin Castle, Gardens & Falconry</h4><p><p>Marvel at the stunning French design of Dunrobin Castle, the most northernly of Scotland&rsquo;s great houses, and the largest in the northern Highlands. Gaze at glorious interiors designed by Scotland&#39;s own Sir Robert Lorimer. Its magnificent architecture and fairy-tale spires were added by Sir Charles Barry, who also designed London&#39;s Houses of Parliament.</p></p><p><p>Marvel at the stunning French design of Dunrobin Castle, the most northernly of Scotland&rsquo;s great houses, and the largest in the northern Highlands. Gaze at glorious interiors designed by Scotland&#39;s own Sir Robert Lorimer. Its magnificent architecture and fairy-tale spires were added by Sir Charles Barry, who also designed London&#39;s Houses of Parliament.</p></p><h4>Experience: Grant Arms Birdwatching & Wildlife Club</h4><p><p>Escape to one of the best areas for bird and wildlife watching in the UK. The Town of Grantown on Spey in the Cairngorms is surrounded by ancient woodlands, which offer a unique habitat for a wide variety of wildlife. Keep your eyes peeled for Gold Eagles, White-tailed Eagle, Pine Martens, Red Squirrel, Slavonian Grebe, Crested Tit and Crossbill, as well as Dolphins, Waders, Sea Ducks and Sea Birds along the Moray Coast. This is an unmissable experience - The Cairngorms were voted one of the Top 20 places to visit in the World by National Geographic Travel magazine!</p></p><p><p>An unmissable experience, The Bird Watching &amp; Wildlife Club (BWWC), established in 2008 at the Grant Arms Hotel (UK&rsquo;s 1st wildlife hotel!), situated in the Cairngorms National Park provides &lsquo;new kind of wildlife watching experience&rsquo; as you discover hidden wildlife spots and see spectacular wildlife which could include* dolphins, red deer, golden eagles, Ospreys all with help from the friendly local wildlife guides *(dependent upon time of year).</p></p><h4>Experience: Balmoral Castle Guided Tour</h4><p></p><p><p>Commissioned by Prince Albert on finding the original to be &lsquo;too small for the family&rsquo;, royal retreat, Scottish baronial-style Balmoral Castle, will be brought to life on your guided tour revealing many stories of noble life. Start by viewing the game larder, iron ballroom and icehouse, before standing on the lawn to admire the view and glory of the granite giant&rsquo;s turreted clocktower. Images courtesy of VisitScotland/North East 250/Damian Shields. Last image curtesy of VisitScotland/Paul Tomkins.</p></p><h4>Experience: Scottish Highlands: Coach Guided Tour</h4><p><p>Our local expert will board the coach and take us on a scenic trail through The Highlands. First stop Dingwall, a fascinating market town brimming with history and hidden treasures, historic buildings, unique shops and great local produce. A light lunch will be provided, before we visit Dunrobin Castle and Gardens to marvel at the stunning French design. The most northerly of Scotland&rsquo;s great houses, and the largest in the Highlands, Dunrobin features glorious interiors designed by Scotland&#39;s own Sir Robert Lorimer, with magnificent architecture and fairy-tale spires added by Sir Charles Barry (designer of London&#39;s Houses of Parliament). On to Inverness, a wonderful wee city in a spectacular location, with breathtaking landscapes and ancient sites of interest. We&rsquo;ll stop for time at leisure in the Capital of the Highlands and a delicious cream before our return to the hotel.</p></p><p><p>Our local expert will board the coach and take us on a 6-hour scenic trail through The Highlands. Starting in Grantown, with a first stop to discover Dingwall for 2 hours and an early lunch; a fascinating market town brimming with history and hidden treasures, unique shops and great local produce. Visits will include Dunrobin Castle and Gardens to marvel at the stunning French design. The most northerly of Scotland&#39;s great houses, and the largest in the Highlands, with glorious interiors designed by Sir Robert Lorimer, and magnificent architecture and fairy-tale spires added by Sir Charles Barry (designer of London&#39;s Houses of Parliament). On to Inverness, a wonderful wee city in a spectacular location, with breathtaking landscapes and ancient sites of interest. Stop for a late lunch and time at leisure in the Capital of the Highlands followed with a relaxed cream tea before a Jacobite Cruise from Clansman Harbour, and our return to the hotel. Images courtesy of VisitScotland/Paul Tomkins ------------------------------------------------------------------- o Coach/tour operator to provide own vehicle (coach) with microphone for use o Guide name and meeting point to be advised no later than 2 weeks prior to arrival o 9.00 departure</p></p><h4>Experience: Leault Working Sheepdog Demonstration</h4><p><p>A unique opportunity that will be the highlight of your holiday. Among beautiful Scottish scenery, see amazing sheepdogs at work on a real working farm, and admire as Neil masterfully directs his working border collies to herd and round the sheep. You may even get an opportunity to help with some sheep shearing (date dependent).</p></p><p><p>A unique opportunity that will be the highlight of your holiday. Among beautiful Scottish scenery, see amazing sheepdogs at work on a real working farm, and admire as Neil masterfully directs his working border collies to herd and round the sheep. You may even get an opportunity to help with some sheep shearing (date dependent).</p></p></body>

